    <h1>REST API</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>Every interface is a RESTful web service based on HTTP/1.1.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The server listens for requests from clients. Each request gets a re=
sponse.</p></li>
<li><p>The body of the request is transmitted in JSON format</p></li>
<li><p>HTTPS is used as transport protocol on port 443</p></li>
<li><p>Exclusively POST requests are used.</p></li>
<li><p>Every request/response has</p>
<ul>
<li><p>a unique ID (reqID)</p></li>
<li><p>a timestamp of the current time (reqTs)<br>The timestamp allows chec=
king the lifetime of the request. The server only accepts requests with a l=
imited lifetime. This allows for easier (and less memory consuming) validit=
y/uniqueness check of the provided reqID.</p></li>
<li><p>a HMAC (credential)<br>The credential is calculated by building a HM=
AC over different fields of the request by use of a dedicated key and is us=
ed to guarantee the authenticity of the request (Refer to 3.3 for details)<=
/p></li>
</ul></li>
<li><p>By using the security elements (reqID, reqTs and credential) each re=
quest is protected against replay attacks and its authenticity is guarantee=
d even if the transport would be done without encryption.</p></li>
<li><p>Versioning: It is possible to set the field "<strong>interface-versi=
on: </strong><em><strong>n</strong></em>" in the HTTP request header to spe=
cify the version of the firmware implementation a client uses. The server n=
eeds to support all versions of an interface to provide backward compatibil=
ity. If "interface-version" is omitted, version 1 will be used.</p></li>
<li><p>Timing: a request shall never take a long time. Usually requests sha=
ll be answered within 200ms at a maximum (100ms shall be targeted).</p></li=
>
</ul>
